---
import Callout from '../../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import Code from '../../../../../components/Code.astro';
import SessionGrid from '../../../../../components/SessionGrid.astro';
import SessionPage from '../../../../../components/SessionPage.astro';
import SessionSection from '../../../../../components/SessionSection.astro';
import TagList from '../../../../../components/TagList.astro';

const before = `app.MapGet("/time", () =>
{
    var zone = "Europe/Warsaw";
    return Results.Ok(new { Zone = zone, Now = DateTimeOffset.UtcNow });
});`;

const options = `public sealed class AppClockOptions
{
    public string Zone { get; set; } = "UTC";
}`;

const appsettings = `{
  "AppClock": {
    "Zone": "Europe/Warsaw"
  }
}`;

const service = `public sealed class AppClock
{
    private readonly AppClockOptions _options;

    public AppClock(AppClockOptions options)
    {
        _options = options;
    }

    public object Snapshot()
    {
        return new
        {
            Zone = _options.Zone,
            Now = DateTimeOffset.UtcNow
        };
    }
}`;

const program = `var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

var clockOptions = builder.Configuration
    .GetSection("AppClock")
    .Get<AppClockOptions>() ?? new AppClockOptions();

builder.Services.AddSingleton(clockOptions);
builder.Services.AddSingleton<AppClock>();

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapGet("/time", (AppClock clock) => Results.Ok(clock.Snapshot()));

app.Run();`;
---

<SessionPage
  title="Session 3 · Dependency injection and configuration"
  heading="DI and configuration: stop hard-coding decisions in handlers"
  lede="Today’s win: separate route code from the objects and settings it depends on."
  backHref="/topics/dotnet/"
  backLabel=".NET sessions"
>
  <SessionSection title="Tiny retrieval first">
    <Callout>
      In the request pipeline, <code>await next(context)</code> continues to the next pipeline step. That next step might be another middleware, endpoint routing, or eventually the matched endpoint handler — not necessarily directly “the next handler.”
    </Callout>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="The first-principles model">
    <p>
      A handler should mostly describe what this endpoint does. It should not personally construct every helper, read every setting, open every client, and decide every lifetime.
    </p>
    <p>
      ASP.NET Core gives you two related tools:
    </p>
    <SessionGrid>
      <div>
        <h3>Configuration</h3>
        <p>Values that come from files, environment variables, command-line arguments, secrets, or hosting settings.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3>Dependency injection</h3>
        <p>A container that knows how to create and provide objects your code asks for.</p>
      </div>
    </SessionGrid>
    <TagList tags={['settings live outside handlers', 'services are registered once', 'handlers ask for what they need']} />
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="The smell: hard-coded work inside the handler">
    <p>
      This endpoint works, but the setting is trapped inside the route handler. Changing it later means editing code.
    </p>
    <Code code={before} lang="csharp" />
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Move settings into configuration">
    <p>
      First create a small options object. Then a configuration source such as <code>appsettings.json</code> can fill it.
    </p>
    <Code code={options} lang="csharp" />
    <Code code={appsettings} lang="json" />
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Move behavior into a service">
    <p>
      A service is just an object with a job. Here, <code>AppClock</code> depends on <code>AppClockOptions</code>. It does not know whether those options came from JSON, environment variables, or tests.
    </p>
    <Code code={service} lang="csharp" />
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Register once, ask where needed">
    <p>
      Before <code>builder.Build()</code>, register the objects the app can provide. Then the endpoint handler asks for <code>AppClock</code> as a parameter.
    </p>
    <Code code={program} lang="csharp" />
    <Callout>
      Mental model: <code>builder.Services</code> is setup time. Handler parameters are request time. The DI container connects the two.
    </Callout>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Retrieval checkpoint — reply in Discord" variant="checkpoint">
    <p>Answer from memory. Short is good:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>In one sentence, what is configuration for?</li>
      <li>In one sentence, what is dependency injection for?</li>
      <li>In the final example, who creates <code>AppClock</code>: the handler, or the DI container?</li>
      <li>Bonus: why is this easier to test than hard-coding <code>"Europe/Warsaw"</code> inside the handler?</li>
    </ol>
  </SessionSection>
</SessionPage>
